"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Matthew chapters 15–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-matthew-15-17.py

Key decisions in this range:
- Canaanite woman (15:21-28): "Son of David" as the messianic title from the Gentile margin;
  her faith exceeds Israel's reception — classified direct revelation
- Corban controversy (15:1-9): Jesus as the authoritative interpreter of Torah, overriding oral
  tradition by appeal to the Father's intention — direct revelation
- Caesarea Philippi (16:13-28): structural pivot of Matthew; "Son of Man" + Peter's "Son of God"
  confession + first passion prediction in one unit — all direct revelation
- Transfiguration (17:1-8): highest OT Christophany; Moses and Elijah give way; Father's voice
  "This is my beloved Son, listen to him" — classified direct revelation (divine voice)
- v16:16 already present; v17:5 already present — skipped in dictionary
- 16:18 (ekklesia) classified as direct revelation — only place Jesus uses the word "church"
- 17:22-23 (second passion prediction): direct revelation of coming suffering and resurrection
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then Pharisees and scribes came to Jesus from Jerusalem and said..." The delegation from Jerusalem — capital city, seat of the Sanhedrin — marks an escalation in the opposition. They come not to learn but to dispute. The Christological frame: Jesus as the authoritative interpreter of Torah is now directly challenged by the institution that claims interpretive authority. The conflict is not merely about handwashing but about who has the right to say what the Torah means — and ultimately, who Jesus is.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct revelation: "Why do your disciples break the tradition of the elders? For they do not wash their hands when they eat." The charge is about <em>paradosis tōn presbyterōn</em> — the oral tradition of the elders, which the Pharisees held to be an authoritative fence around Torah. Jesus will invert this: the tradition of the elders breaks the commandment of God (v.3). The Christological claim is implicit: Jesus\' authority exceeds the accumulated authority of all the elders; he speaks as the one who knows the Father\'s intention directly (11:27).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct revelation: "He answered them, \'And why do you break the commandment of God for the sake of your tradition?\'" The counter-question shifts the terrain: the accusation of breaking tradition is answered by the accusation of breaking the commandment of God. Jesus here positions himself as the defender of the Father\'s actual intent against the human accumulation that distorts it. This is the claim of the one who knows the Father perfectly — not merely an interpreter but the Son who speaks from within the divine mind.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "For God commanded, \'Honor your father and your mother,\' and \'Whoever reviles father or mother must surely die.\'" The citation of Exod 20:12 and Exod 21:17 establishes God\'s commandment as the standard by which the Corban tradition is judged. Jesus speaks as the one who knows what God commanded — with the authority of the giver, not merely the receiver, of the commandment. The appeal to the divine "commanded" versus the human "tradition" is the hermeneutical key to the entire controversy.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct revelation: "But you say, \'If anyone tells his father or his mother, what you would have gained from me is given to God...\'" The Corban ruling allowed a person to declare resources dedicated to the Temple (<em>qorban</em>), which released them from the obligation to support aging parents. Jesus identifies this as a device for voiding the commandment of God under a veneer of piety. The Christological bearing: the one who came to fulfill the Law (5:17) exposes the way human tradition has emptied the Law of its content.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation: "He need not honor his father. So for the sake of your tradition you have made void the word of God." The verb "made void" (<em>ēkyrōsate</em>) is a legal term — annulled, invalidated. Jesus issues a legal ruling against the ruling of the Pharisees. The authority behind this counter-ruling is not precedent or argument from tradition but the direct authority of the Son who knows what the Father commanded. This is the Christological shape of Jesus\' teaching throughout: he speaks as one who has authority (7:29), not as the scribes.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "You hypocrites! Well did Isaiah prophesy of you, when he said..." The citation of Isaiah as prophetically addressed to the Pharisees is a Christological move: Jesus reads the prophetic text as speaking about the present moment. He is the one who can make this identification — the prophet saw this generation\'s hardness, and Jesus names it. The word "hypocrites" (<em>hypokritai</em>, stage actors) charges them with performing religion while the heart is absent.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "\'This people honors me with their lips, but their heart is far from me.\'" The citation of Isa 29:13 (LXX) identifies the Pharisaic practice as the fulfillment of Isaiah\'s diagnosis of Israel\'s lip-service religion. The Christological weight: Jesus speaks as the one to whom lips and hearts are directed — "honors me" is the God-directed worship that the Pharisees perform externally while their hearts are absent. The claim is that they honor not merely God in the abstract but the one standing before them, while their hearts reject him.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "In vain do they worship me, teaching as doctrines the commandments of men." The Isaiah citation continues: worship becomes vain when it is governed by human commandments rather than divine ones. The Christological application: Jesus is the one who can adjudicate the difference between divine and human commandments because he is the Son who knows the Father\'s will directly. He quotes Isaiah not as a precedent but as a prophecy of the present — the fulfiller who recognizes the pattern.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he called the people to him and said to them, \'Hear and understand:\'" The call to hearing and understanding — the refrain of the parable discourse (13:9, 43) — now addresses the crowd rather than only the Pharisees. Jesus invites the people to receive his authoritative teaching on what defiles. The Christological posture: he does not retreat to a private setting but speaks publicly and commands understanding. He is the teacher who both demands and enables comprehension.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct revelation: "It is not what goes into the mouth that defiles a person, but what comes out of the mouth; this defiles a person." This saying overturns the entire logic of food purity in one sentence — a more radical act than the Pharisees\' Corban ruling. The Christological authority is immense: Jesus effectively sets aside the food purity laws of Leviticus 11 by a single authoritative declaration. Mark 7:19 notes that Jesus "declared all foods clean." This is the authority of the one who gave the laws in the first place and who now declares their eschatological fulfillment.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then the disciples came and said to him, \'Do you know that the Pharisees were offended when they heard this saying?\'" The disciples\' concern about Pharisaic offense is the pastoral worry of those who must live in religious society. The Christological response (v.13-14) reveals that Jesus is not calibrating his teaching to avoid offense — he is saying what is true regardless of its reception. The stone of stumbling (Isa 8:14) causes offense precisely because it is real.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct revelation: "He answered, \'Every plant that my heavenly Father has not planted will be rooted up.\'" The Father\'s planting versus human tradition is the eschatological standard. What the Father has not planted cannot stand — including the Pharisaic system that has replaced divine commandment with human tradition. The Christological claim: Jesus speaks about "my heavenly Father" with the intimacy of the Son (11:27), and what the Father plants versus uproots is known to the Son who speaks from within that relationship.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "Let them alone; they are blind guides. And if the blind lead the blind, both will fall into a pit." The blind-guides image is a Christological indictment: the leaders entrusted with guiding Israel to the Messiah cannot see the one standing before them. The blindness is not intellectual but volitional — they have closed their eyes (13:15). The Christological irony: the guides who should have recognized and proclaimed the Messiah are the ones who will engineer his death.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "But Peter said to him, \'Explain to us the parable.\'" Peter\'s request for explanation mirrors the disciples\' pattern of seeking understanding (13:10, 36). The Christological pedagogy continues: the disciples receive the inside track of explanation that the crowds and Pharisees do not. Peter\'s later confession (16:16) comes from a disciple who has been consistently brought inside the teaching that others reject.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he said, \'Are you also still without understanding?\'" The gentle rebuke — "still without understanding" — is the Christological patience of the teacher who has explained much and finds his closest followers still at the beginning. The word "still" implies expectation: after all they have heard and seen, understanding should be further along. The Christological demand is not merely intellectual assent but transformative comprehension that is still developing in the disciples.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "Do you not see that whatever goes into the mouth passes into the stomach and is expelled?" The physiological explanation — food enters, passes through, exits — grounds the theological principle in common bodily knowledge. The Christological move: Jesus appeals to what everyone knows about the body to expose what the Pharisees have missed about the heart. The teacher who speaks with authority does not disdain ordinary knowledge but uses it to illuminate divine intention.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct revelation: "But what comes out of the mouth proceeds from the heart, and this defiles a person." The heart as the source of defilement locates the problem of sin at its root. The Christological bearing: the one who teaches about the heart\'s defilement is the same one who will bear the full weight of human-heart darkness in the passion. The purity of Jesus\' own heart — tested in the wilderness, sustained through the ministry — is the contrast to the defilement he diagnoses.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "For out of the heart come evil thoughts, murder, adultery, sexual immorality, theft, false witness, slander." The catalog of vices from the heart is the internal catalog that corresponds to the external commandments (commandments 6-9 of the Decalogue). The Christological bearing: Jesus has already addressed these vices in the Sermon on the Mount (5:21-30) as the heart-level interpretation of Torah. The one who taught the heart-standard now explains why the heart is the source of defilement — and why only a new heart (promised in Jer 31:33; Ezek 36:26) can resolve the problem.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "These are what defile a person. But to eat with unwashed hands does not defile a person." The closing verdict settles the controversy: ritual handwashing is not a defilement issue; the heart\'s vices are. The Christological authority: Jesus has adjudicated the question authoritatively, appealing to the Father\'s commandment over the elders\' tradition. The verdict is not subject to appeal — he speaks as the one who knows what the Father intends.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct revelation: "And Jesus went away from there and withdrew to the district of Tyre and Sidon." The withdrawal to Tyre and Sidon — Gentile territory on the Phoenician coast — is a geographical Christological statement. Jesus moves outside Israel\'s borders following the Pharisees\' opposition. The Gentile territory will produce a faith that the religious leaders of Israel have rejected. The movement from Jewish controversy to Gentile faith is the pattern of the book of Acts, anticipated here.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct revelation: "And behold, a Canaanite woman from that region came out and was crying, \'Have mercy on me, O Lord, Son of David; my daughter is severely oppressed by a demon.\'" The Canaanite woman\'s cry is a Christological confession from the Gentile margin: "Lord, Son of David" is the full messianic title — lordship and Davidic lineage together. The depth of the irony: the Pharisees from Jerusalem question Jesus\' authority; a Canaanite woman recognizes and confesses it. Her cry "have mercy on me" is the prayer of the Psalms (Ps 41:4, 10; 51:1) addressed to the Messiah.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "But he did not answer her a word. And his disciples came and begged him, saying, \'Send her away, for she is crying out after us.\'" The silence of Jesus — not dismissal but testing — creates the space for the woman\'s persistent faith to be revealed. The disciples\' request to send her away reflects their own ethnic and social boundaries. The Christological drama: the silence is not indifference but the condition in which the genuineness of her faith can emerge. The test of silence is a more profound form of encounter than immediate response.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "He answered, \'I was sent only to the lost sheep of the house of Israel.\'" The limitation of Jesus\' earthly mission to Israel (cf. 10:5-6) is stated frankly. The Christological logic: the Son came first to Israel, fulfilling the covenantal priority of salvation (Rom 1:16: "to the Jew first"). This is not rejection of Gentiles in principle but sequential fulfillment of the OT promise — Israel first, then the nations. The Great Commission (28:19) will reverse the restriction after the resurrection.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation: "But she came and knelt before him, saying, \'Lord, help me.\'" The woman\'s prostration and petition — "Lord, help me" — is worship and prayer directed to Jesus. The shortening of the prayer to its essential core ("Lord, help me") is the cry of utter dependence. The Christological bearing: she has heard his statement of limitation (v.24) and presses past it, trusting in his mercy beyond the stated boundary. The faith that persists past the apparent refusal is the faith that receives what it seeks.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he answered, \'It is not right to take the children\'s bread and throw it to the dogs.\'" The metaphor of children and dogs — Israel and Gentiles in the common Jewish idiom — restates the missionary priority. The Christological tension: Jesus uses the very language that would exclude her to create the opening for her response. The dogs (<em>kynarion</em>, little dogs, household dogs — not the street dogs of insult) are in the house; they are not strangers to the master\'s table but domestic animals who receive crumbs. The diminutive is merciful.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "She said, \'Yes, Lord, yet even the dogs eat the crumbs that fall from their masters\' table.\'" The woman\'s response is a masterpiece of faithful argumentation: she accepts the metaphor, accepts her position as a dog, and finds within it the ground of hope. The crumbs from the master\'s table are more than enough. The Christological bearing: her faith grasps the overflow of the kingdom\'s abundance — that even the edges of Jesus\' ministry are sufficient to heal. She does not ask for Israel\'s portion but for the residue of mercy.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then Jesus answered her, \'O woman, great is your faith! Be it done for you as you desire.\' And her daughter was healed instantly." The exclamation "O woman, great is your faith!" (<em>ō gynai, megalē sou hē pistis</em>) is the highest commendation in Matthew — paralleling only the centurion\'s faith (8:10: "not even in Israel have I found such faith"). The immediate healing confirms the commendation. The Christological revelation: the Gentile woman\'s persistent faith in the Messiah receives what Israel\'s religious establishment has rejected — the mercy of the Son of David.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: "Jesus went on from there and walked beside the Sea of Galilee. And he went up on the mountain and sat down there." The return to the Galilean lakeside and the mountain setting mirrors the Sermon on the Mount (5:1) and the Feeding of the 5000 (14:23). Jesus sits in the teacher\'s posture. The mountain in Matthew is consistently the locus of divine encounter: teaching (5:1), prayer (14:23), transfiguration (17:1), commission (28:16). The mountain-sitting signals that a significant revelation follows.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "And great crowds came to him, bringing with them the lame, the blind, the crippled, the mute, and many others, and they put them at his feet, and he healed them." The catalog of healings — lame, blind, crippled, mute — is the fulfillment of Isa 35:5-6 ("the eyes of the blind shall be opened, and the ears of the deaf unstopped; the lame man shall leap like a deer, and the tongue of the mute shall sing for joy"). The messianic healing agenda is systematically fulfilled. The crowds who put the sick "at his feet" are in the posture of worship before the healer.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "So that the crowd marveled, when they saw the mute speaking, the crippled healthy, the lame walking, and the blind seeing. And they glorified the God of Israel." The glorification of "the God of Israel" by the crowd echoes the setting (Gentile territory) and the sequence: the messianic healings in Gentile regions cause Gentiles to glorify the God of Israel. This is the fulfillment of Isa 42:6-7 (the servant as "a light for the nations, to open eyes that are blind"). The healer brings Gentile worship to the God of Israel through his works.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then Jesus called his disciples to him and said, \'I have compassion on the crowd because they have been with me now three days and have nothing to eat. And I am not willing to send them away hungry, lest they faint on the way.\'" The compassion statement parallels 14:14 (the feeding of the 5000); the three-day period mirrors the wilderness wandering\'s food crisis. The Christological bearing: Jesus does not send away the hungry. "I am not willing to send them away hungry" is the divine refusal to abandon the needy — echoing the divine shepherd of Ezek 34 who does not scatter the flock but feeds it.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "And the disciples said to him, \'Where are we to get enough bread in such a desolate place to feed so great a crowd?\'" The disciples\' question — after already having witnessed the feeding of the 5000 (14:19) — reveals the limits of their comprehension. The same "desolate place" (<em>erēmia</em>), the same insufficiency, the same crowd: yet they ask where bread will come from. The Christological patience: Jesus answers the question of inadequate resources with the same action as before, teaching the disciples by repetition that his provision is not exhausted by one miracle.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "And Jesus said to them, \'How many loaves do you have?\' They said, \'Seven, and a few small fish.\'" The inventory of inadequacy is again precise: seven loaves, a few small fish. The Christological pattern repeats: bring what you have to me, and I will multiply it. The number seven (unlike the five of 14:17) has symbolic resonance — seven is the number of completeness in the OT. The feeding of the 4000 mirrors the feeding of the 5000, with variations that suggest both events are real and distinct.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "And directing the crowd to sit down on the ground." The command to sit (<em>anapesein</em>, to recline — the table-fellowship posture) is the same as the feeding of the 5000 (14:19). The reclining crowd is placed in the posture of the eschatological banquet (8:11: "many will recline with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven"). The Christological host provides not a standing meal but a feast of rest — the same abundance of the messianic banquet enacted in ordinary bread and fish.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A type: "He took the seven loaves and the fish, and having given thanks he broke them and gave them to the disciples, and the disciples gave them to the crowds." The eucharistic formula — took, gave thanks, broke, gave — is identical to 14:19 and the Last Supper (26:26-27). The threefold repetition of the eucharistic action (5000, 4000, Last Supper) weaves the feeding miracles together as anticipations of the table where Christ gives himself. The disciples as distributors are the mediation-pattern of the church\'s ministry.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A type: "And they all ate and were satisfied. And they took up seven baskets full of the broken pieces left over." The seven baskets (as opposed to twelve in 14:20) may correspond to the seven nations of Canaan (Deut 7:1) or the seventy nations of Gen 10, signaling the Gentile dimension of the feeding. The superabundance — seven baskets of leftovers after all were satisfied — is the signature of divine provision: more than enough, with surplus. The kingdom\'s table does not run short.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A type: "Those who ate were four thousand men, besides women and children." The four thousand (plus women and children — a larger total than the named figure) in Gentile territory parallels the five thousand in Jewish territory. Together the two feedings span both peoples. The Christological scope: Jesus feeds both Jewish and Gentile crowds in the wilderness — the new Moses provision extends to all nations before the Great Commission makes it explicit.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A revelation of God: "And after sending away the crowds, he got into the boat and went to the region of Magadan." The departure by boat follows the pattern of ch.14 (withdrawal after feeding, sea crossing). The region of Magadan (possibly Magdala/Dalmanutha on the western shore of Galilee) is the transition point between the Gentile mission and the return to Jewish controversy (16:1: Pharisees and Sadducees demanding a sign). The geography of Jesus\' ministry traces the kingdom\'s expanding circle: Jewish controversy, Gentile healing and feeding, return to Jewish questioning.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: "And the Pharisees and Sadducees came, and to test him they asked him to show them a sign from heaven." The joint delegation of Pharisees and Sadducees — normally rivals — united in opposition to Jesus is a significant Christological marker. The demand for a "sign from heaven" implicitly rejects all the healings and feeding miracles as insufficient. The Christological claim these miracles make is too threatening to both parties; they demand something that can\'t be attributed to Beelzebul (cf. 12:24). The test is not genuine inquiry but a trap.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "He answered them, \'When it is evening, you say, \'It will be fair weather, for the sky is red.\'" The weather-reading analogy sets up the irony of v.3: those who can read natural signs cannot read the signs of the times. The Christological bearing: Jesus has been performing the messianic signs catalogued by Isaiah throughout his ministry. Those who would read the sky cannot read the one who stills the sky (8:26) and walks on its waters (14:25).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "And in the morning, \'It will be stormy today, for the sky is red and threatening.\' You know how to interpret the appearance of the sky, but you cannot interpret the signs of the times." The "signs of the times" (<em>sēmeia tōn kairōn</em>) are the eschatological indicators of the kingdom\'s arrival. Jesus has been performing them: blind see, lame walk, deaf hear, dead raised, poor have good news preached (11:5 — the signs Isaiah specified). The inability to read these signs is the hardness of heart that Isaiah prophesied (13:14-15). The Christological indictment: the ones who should recognize the Messiah\'s arrival are deliberately blind to it.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct revelation: "An evil and adulterous generation seeks for a sign, but no sign will be given to it except the sign of Jonah." The only sign offered is the sign of Jonah — already explained in 12:40 as the three days and nights, a type of the resurrection. The Christological precision: the one miracle that will vindicate all his claims, authenticate all his signs, and expose the blindness of his opponents is the resurrection. All other signs performed before unbelief are insufficient; only the resurrection sign will break open what nothing else could. He left them and departed.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "When the disciples reached the other side, they had forgotten to bring any bread." The disciples\' forgetfulness — occurring immediately after two feeding miracles — is the practical occasion for the warning about leaven. The Christological irony: the disciples who just watched Jesus feed thousands are anxious about a forgotten loaf. The anxiety about bread is the very state of heart that Jesus addresses: those who have seen the provision should not be anxious about insufficiency (6:25-34).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation: "Jesus said to them, \'Watch and beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees.\'" The warning about leaven — the small amount that permeates the whole batch (13:33) — is a Christological warning about the subtle pervasiveness of false teaching. The leaven of the Pharisees is the doctrine (v.12) that closes the heart to the Messiah standing before them. The one who gave the leaven parable now warns against the kingdom-leaven\'s opposite: the leaven that permeates the whole with darkness rather than light.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "And they began discussing it among themselves, saying, \'We brought no bread.\'" The disciples interpret the leaven-warning literally — a misreading that Jesus corrects with increasing exasperation. The Christological pedagogy: the disciples\' literalism is the failure to make the interpretive move that Jesus has been training them to make. The teacher who speaks in parables must be heard parabolically; those who hear literally have not yet learned the hermeneutic of the kingdom.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "But Jesus, aware of this, said, \'O you of little faith, why are you discussing among yourselves the fact that you have no bread?\'" The "little faith" charge (<em>oligopistoi</em>) — used also at 6:30; 8:26; 14:31 — is the consistent Christological diagnosis of the disciples\' condition. They have received much: they have followed, witnessed, been taught. Yet anxiety about bread reveals a faith that has not yet been fully transformed by what it has seen. The awareness of Jesus ("aware of this" before they speak to him) is itself a Christological marker.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "Do you not yet perceive? Do you not remember the five loaves for the five thousand, and how many baskets you took up?" The appeal to memory — "do you not remember?" — is the Christological call to build faith on accumulated evidence. The disciples\' anxiety about bread in the presence of the one who fed 5000 and 4000 is the failure to integrate experience into faith. The Christological teacher does not merely repeat miracles; he calls the disciples to interpret the pattern of what they have already witnessed.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "Or the seven loaves for the four thousand, and how many baskets you took up?" The double appeal to both feeding miracles makes the point: two occasions, two different numbers, the same superabundant provision. The repetition is the redundancy of divine grace — not once but twice, not one people but two. The Christological abundance has been demonstrated across multiple occasions and populations. There is no excuse for bread-anxiety in the presence of this teacher.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "How is it that you fail to understand that I did not speak about bread? Beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees." The frustration of the teacher who must re-explain is the Christological patience of the one who keeps speaking until understanding comes. The leaven-warning is finally decoded as doctrinal warning — the system of interpretation that cannot see the Messiah. The Christological stake: the leaven of Pharisees and Sadducees is the hermeneutical failure that will engineer the crucifixion.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then they understood that he did not tell them to beware of the leaven of bread, but of the teaching of the Pharisees and Sadducees." The disciples\' understanding — delayed but genuine — is the pattern of Matthean discipleship: gradual comprehension that comes through persistence with the teacher. The identification of the leaven as "teaching" (<em>didachē</em>) specifies the danger: not the Pharisees themselves but their interpretive system, their doctrine about who the Messiah is and what the kingdom looks like. False doctrine is the leaven that corrupts.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct revelation: "Now when Jesus came into the district of Caesarea Philippi, he asked his disciples, \'Who do people say that the Son of Man is?\'" The Caesarea Philippi question is the Christological pivot of Matthew. The location — a Gentile city at the foot of Mount Hermon, built by Philip the tetrarch — is deliberately chosen: the confession of Christ\'s identity occurs at the margin, away from Jerusalem, in Gentile territory. The "Son of Man" as self-referential title carries the full Danielic weight of the eschatological judge and ruler (Dan 7:13-14).</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "And they said, \'Some say John the Baptist, others say Elijah, and others Jeremiah or one of the prophets.\'" The popular identifications — all prophetic figures — reveal what the crowd has perceived: Jesus is extraordinary, eschatologically significant, perhaps the herald of the end. But they place him within the prophetic tradition rather than above it. The Christological inadequacy: all these identifications are too small. John announced Jesus; Elijah was a type of John (11:14). Jesus is not a prophet in the series but the one to whom all the prophets pointed.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation: "He said to them, \'But who do you say that I am?\'" The direct question to the disciples — "but you (<em>de humeis</em>), who do you say?" — distinguishes their answer from the crowd\'s. The disciples have been given to know the secrets of the kingdom (13:11); now the question tests whether that knowledge has crystallized into confession. The Christological demand: Jesus does not ask only for acknowledgment but for personal, confessional identification. "Who do you say I am?" is the question every hearer must answer.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct revelation: "And Jesus answered him, \'Blessed are you, Simon Bar-Jonah! For flesh and blood has not revealed this to you, but my Father who is in heaven.\'" The beatitude on Peter is the Christological affirmation that divine revelation is the source of the confession "Son of the living God." The knowledge of Christ\'s identity is not achievable by human inquiry (<em>sarx kai haima</em>, flesh and blood) — it is the gift of the Father who reveals the Son (11:27). Peter\'s confession comes from the same divine disclosure that makes all genuine faith possible.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct revelation: "And I tell you, you are Peter, and on this rock I will build my church, and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it." The wordplay (<em>Petros / petra</em>, Peter / rock) makes Peter the named foundation of the community Jesus will build. The "church" (<em>ekklēsia</em>) is Jesus\' only use of the word in Matthew — and his ownership of it is total: "my church." The gates of hell (<em>hadou</em>) not prevailing is the image of death\'s power unable to hold what Christ builds. The resurrection is implied: not even death can overpower the community built on the confession of the Son of God.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A direct revelation: "I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven, and whatever you bind on earth shall be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth shall be loosed in heaven." The keys of the kingdom — the authority to admit and exclude, to declare binding and free — are given by the one who holds all authority in heaven and on earth (28:18). The Christological source: the binding and loosing authority delegated to Peter (and the community, 18:18) is delegated from the one who has it absolutely. The keyholder grants key-authority.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then he strictly charged the disciples to tell no one that he was the Christ." The messianic secret — tell no one — is the Christological economy of the Markan pattern continued in Matthew: the revelation of identity comes at the Father\'s appointed time, through the passion and resurrection, not through premature proclamation. The disciples who now know must not yet broadcast what they know because the knowledge without the cross would be incomplete — the Son of God without the suffering servant.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct revelation: "From that time Jesus began to show his disciples that he must go to Jerusalem and suffer many things from the elders and chief priests and scribes, and be killed, and on the third day be raised." The first explicit passion prediction is the Christological turn of the Gospel. "From that time" marks the watershed: having established his identity (v.16), Jesus now reveals his mission — not triumph but suffering, death, and resurrection. The "must" (<em>dei</em>) is the divine necessity: this is not an accident or failure but the Father\'s appointed path for the Son.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct revelation: "And Peter took him aside and began to rebuke him, saying, \'Far be it from you, Lord! This shall never happen to you.\'" Peter\'s rebuke — immediately following his inspired confession — is the measure of how far even genuine faith can miss the Christological necessity of suffering. "Far be it from you" (<em>hileōs soi, Kyrie</em>) is protective dismissal of the passion. The Christological irony: the one who just received divine revelation about Christ\'s identity now tries to redirect Christ away from his mission. The confessor becomes the rebuker in a single breath.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct revelation: "But he turned and said to Peter, \'Get behind me, Satan! You are a hindrance to me. For you are not setting your mind on the things of God, but on the things of men.\'" The rebuke of Peter as "Satan" is the sharpest Christological statement in Matthew. The one who confessed Jesus correctly now speaks Satan\'s agenda: offering the kingdom without the cross. The Christological logic: the path of glory through avoidance of suffering is the same path Satan offered in the wilderness (4:8-9). The hindrance (<em>skandalon</em>) is the same word for the stumbling-block — Peter\'s human thinking about power without the cross is the ultimate stumbling-block.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then Jesus told his disciples, \'If anyone would come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross and follow me.\'" The cross-shaped discipleship is the Christological extension of the cross-shaped mission. The same path Jesus will walk — self-denial, death, following — is the path he calls all disciples to walk. The "cross" before the crucifixion is the eschatological shape of following: the disciples are called to take up the instrument of their own execution and walk behind the one who will carry his. Discipleship is death, and death is the path to resurrection life.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation: "For whoever would save his life will lose it, but whoever loses his life for my sake will find it." The paradox of losing-to-find is the Christological inversion of all natural human strategy. The one who clings to self-preservation loses; the one who gives up the self for Christ\'s sake finds — because Christ himself is the one who loses his life (27:50) and finds it again (28:6). The disciple participates in the Christ-pattern: death leads to resurrection, self-giving leads to self-finding, in union with the crucified and risen Lord.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation: "For what will it profit a man if he gains the whole world and forfeits his soul? Or what shall a man give in return for his soul?" The soul\'s infinite worth — exceeding "the whole world" — is the Christological value-claim that undergirds the cross-call. Christ did not come to save property or status but souls; the one who calls disciples to lose their lives knows the infinite value of what is at stake. The question "what will a man give in return for his soul?" is answered by Christ\'s own offering: he gives himself for the soul\'s redemption (20:28).</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "For the Son of Man is going to come with his angels in the glory of his Father, and then he will repay each person according to what he has done." The eschatological coming of the Son of Man — with his angels, in the glory of the Father — is the Danielic vision (Dan 7:13-14) applied to Jesus\' personal return. The "glory of his Father" identifies the Son of Man\'s glory as the Father\'s glory — the shared glory of the eternal Son made manifest at the consummation. The judgment ("repay each according to what he has done") is the Son of Man\'s eschatological role as universal judge.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation: "Truly, I say to you, there are some standing here who will not taste death until they see the Son of Man coming in his kingdom." The "some standing here" who will see the Son of Man\'s kingdom before death has been interpreted as the Transfiguration (17:1-8), Pentecost, the destruction of Jerusalem, or the resurrection. Most naturally it refers to the Transfiguration — six days later, three disciples see the kingdom\'s glory in preview. The Christological weight: the glory of the Son of Man\'s kingdom is not merely future but is about to be disclosed as present and real.</p>'
  },
  "17": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: "And after six days Jesus took with him Peter and James, and John his brother, and led them up a high mountain by themselves." The six-day interval connects the Transfiguration to the Caesarea Philippi confession-and-passion-prediction sequence. The three disciples taken up the mountain are the inner circle who will also be taken to Gethsemane (26:37). The high mountain echoes Sinai (Exod 24:1, where Moses took Aaron, Nadab, and Abihu up the mountain to see God). Jesus is leading his disciples into a theophanic encounter that mirrors and surpasses Sinai.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct revelation: "And he was transfigured before them, and his face shone like the sun, and his clothes became white as light." The transfiguration (<em>metemorphōthē</em>) is the disclosure of the divine glory that the Son carries within his human form. The shining face recalls Moses\' face after the divine encounter (Exod 34:29-35), but Jesus\' glory shines from within — he is not reflecting divine glory but radiating his own. The white-as-light clothing echoes the angel-at-the-tomb description (28:3) and the heavenly figures of Daniel 7:9 and 10:6. This is the pre-resurrection glory of the Son.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct revelation: "And behold, there appeared to them Moses and Elijah, talking with him." Moses and Elijah — the Law and the Prophets — appear at the Transfiguration as the representatives of the entire OT witness to Jesus. Moses (the giver of Torah who spoke with YHWH face-to-face) and Elijah (the great prophet who was taken up into heaven) flank the Son, their presence declaring: everything they represent finds its fulfillment here. Luke 9:31 reveals the subject of their conversation: his "departure" (exodus), the death-and-resurrection he is about to accomplish in Jerusalem.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "And Peter said to Jesus, \'Lord, it is good that we are here. If you wish, I will make three tents here, one for you and one for Moses and one for Elijah.\'" Peter\'s proposal to build three booths (sukkot — the wilderness dwelling structures of the Feast of Booths, Lev 23:42-43) is the attempt to institutionalize the theophanic moment, to dwell in the glory permanently. The Christological problem: three tents place Moses, Elijah, and Jesus on equal footing. The Father\'s voice (v.5) corrects this immediately. Peter\'s impulse is right (to remain in the presence) but the theology is wrong (the three are not equals).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation: "When the disciples heard this, they fell on their faces and were terrified." The prostration before the divine voice is the standard OT theophanic response: falling on the face before the overwhelming divine presence (Gen 17:3; Ezek 1:28; Dan 8:17; 10:9). The terror (<em>ephobēthēsan sphodra</em>) is the correct response to the holy — not comfort but the awe that recognizes it has encountered something beyond human categories. The disciples have not fallen before an angel or a prophet but before the voice of the living God identifying his Son.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct revelation: "But Jesus came and touched them, saying, \'Rise, and have no fear.\'" The touch of Jesus that dissolves terror is the mediatorial action of the one who bridges the divine and human. The same voice that commands "this is my beloved Son" (the divine declaration of identity) becomes the hand that touches the prostrate disciples. "Rise and have no fear" (<em>egerthēte kai mē phobeisthe</em>) is the resurrection-word (<em>egerthēte</em>) before the resurrection — the same word Jesus will use after Easter (28:6: <em>ēgerthē</em>). The Transfiguration is the pre-resurrection disclosure of what the resurrection will reveal.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct revelation: "And when they lifted up their eyes, they saw no one but Jesus only." The climax of the Transfiguration is the simplest Christological statement: Moses and Elijah have gone; the voice has spoken and fallen silent; and the disciples see "no one but Jesus only" (<em>Iēsoun monon</em>). The Law and the Prophets have been absorbed into him; the divine voice has identified him; and the disciples are left with Christ alone. The Christological summation: at the end of every theophany, every divine encounter, every revelation — only Jesus remains. He is the sum and content of all that God has to say.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct revelation: "And as they were coming down the mountain, Jesus commanded them, \'Tell no one the vision, until the Son of Man is raised from the dead.\'" The seal of silence until the resurrection is the Christological economy of disclosure: the Transfiguration\'s meaning cannot be properly understood until the resurrection completes it. The glory seen on the mountain is the preview of the resurrection glory; without the cross and empty tomb, the Transfiguration would be misread as a triumph without suffering. "The Son of Man is raised from the dead" is stated here as the interpretive key to everything the disciples have just seen.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct revelation: "And the disciples asked him, \'Then why do the scribes say that first Elijah must come?\'" The disciples\' question about Elijah — prompted by seeing Elijah on the mountain — is a Christological query about the order of eschatological events. Malachi 4:5-6 promises that Elijah will come before the great and dreadful day of the LORD. If Jesus is the Messiah, where is Elijah? The question reveals that the disciples are beginning to connect the prophetic pattern to the present moment — they are doing eschatological theology in real time.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct revelation: "He answered, \'Elijah does come, and he will restore all things.\'" Jesus affirms the Elijah tradition before applying it to John the Baptist. The "restoration of all things" (<em>apokatastēsei panta</em>) is the cosmic renewal promised in the prophets — what Acts 3:21 calls the "restoration of all things that God spoke by the mouth of his holy prophets." The Christological frame: the coming of Elijah (John) inaugurates the restoration sequence, and Jesus is the one who will accomplish it. John prepared the way; Jesus will restore all things through the cross and resurrection.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct revelation: "But I tell you that Elijah has already come, and they did not recognize him, but did to him whatever they pleased. So also the Son of Man will suffer at their hands." The identification of John as the already-come Elijah is paired with the passion prediction for Jesus. The pattern is explicit: the forerunner came and was killed; the Son of Man will follow the same path. The Christological parallel: John\'s rejection and death prefigures Jesus\' rejection and death. The same powers that silenced the herald will silence the proclaimed one — but only for three days.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then the disciples understood that he was speaking to them of John the Baptist." The disciples\' understanding — explicit and confirmed — is the progressive comprehension that follows each revelation. They now have the hermeneutical key: John = Elijah, Jesus = Son of Man, rejection of John = preview of rejection of Jesus. The Christological education continues: the disciples are being formed to understand the pattern of rejection-then-vindication that governs all of redemptive history.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "And when they came to the crowd, a man came up to him and, kneeling before him, said, \'Lord, have mercy on my son, for he has seizures and he suffers terribly. For often he falls into the fire, and often into the water.\'" The descent from the Transfiguration to the valley of demonic torment is the Christological movement of the incarnation in miniature: from divine glory into the suffering of the world. The kneeling father\'s petition ("Lord, have mercy") is the prayer of the Psalms directed to the one whose glory has just been revealed. From the mountain of transfiguration to the valley of suffering — this is where the Lord\'s mercy operates.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "And I brought him to your disciples, and they could not heal him." The disciples\' failure to heal the epileptic boy is the Christological test of their received authority (10:1: Jesus gave them authority over unclean spirits). The failure is not a permanent limitation but the occasion for instruction. The Christological bearing: the disciples\' inadequacy is the space in which Jesus\' sufficiency is revealed — and the occasion for teaching about the faith that accesses that sufficiency (v.20).</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "And I brought him to your disciples, and they could not heal him." (See v.15 — this verse continues the father\'s report.) The juxtaposition of the disciples\' failure with Jesus\' immediate healing (v.18) is the Christological contrast between delegated authority poorly appropriated and the original authority of the Son. The disciples have the authority but not yet the faith to exercise it consistently. The teacher\'s authority and the disciples\' authority are the same kind but not the same degree.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct revelation: "And Jesus answered, \'O faithless and twisted generation, how long am I to be with you? How long am I to bear with you? Bring him here to me.\'" The cry "how long am I to be with you?" is the Christological statement of the Incarnation\'s temporariness: Jesus knows his time is limited, and the disciples\' continued failure to exercise the faith entrusted to them is a burden to him. The "faithless and twisted generation" echoes Moses\' lament at Israel\'s unbelief in the wilderness (Deut 32:5, 20). Jesus is the new Moses bearing with a generation that will not fully believe.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct revelation: "And Jesus rebuked the demon, and it came out of him, and the boy was healed instantly." The immediate healing — in contrast to the disciples\' failed attempt — is the Christological demonstration of the authority that the disciples are called to exercise. The rebuke of the demon is the authority of the Son of God (8:29: the demons recognized Jesus as "Son of God"). The instant healing is the signature of his presence: "as many as touched him were healed" (14:36). His authority is not effortful but inherent.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then the disciples came to Jesus privately and said, \'Why could we not cast it out?\'" The private question — asked in the pattern of the parable-explanations (13:10, 36) — is the disciples\' honest acknowledgment of failure and desire to understand. The Christological pedagogy: the disciples who fail and then ask are the disciples who learn. The failure, the question, and the private teaching are the threefold pattern of Matthean discipleship formation.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A direct revelation: "He said to them, \'Because of your little faith. For truly, I say to you, if you have faith like a grain of mustard seed, you will say to this mountain, \'Move from here to there,\' and it will move, and nothing will be impossible for you.\'" The mustard seed of faith (the smallest seed, 13:31) that moves mountains is the paradox of kingdom power: not the size of faith but its object. Faith in the one who has all authority can do what the authority-holder can do — and "nothing will be impossible." The Christological basis: faith that is directed to the Son of God, who holds all authority, participates in his omnipotence. The disciples\' failure was not insufficient faith but misdirected or insufficient trust in the one who authorized them.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: (v.21 absent in many manuscripts — "this kind does not come out except by prayer and fasting" — but present in some tradition.) Even in the textual tradition that includes this verse, the principle is Christological: the deep work of spiritual warfare requires the dependence on God that prayer and fasting cultivate. The disciples\' independence from the Father in their attempt to heal is the root of their failure; dependence is the posture of kingdom authority.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct revelation: "As they were gathering in Galilee, Jesus said to them, \'The Son of Man is about to be delivered into the hands of men.\'" The second passion prediction introduces the theme of being "delivered" (<em>paradidosthai</em>) — the same verb used for Judas\'s betrayal (26:25) and for the handing-over to the Gentiles (27:2). The passive implies divine agency: the Son of Man is "delivered" according to the Father\'s plan. The gathering in Galilee before the journey to Jerusalem gives the passion prediction its geographical urgency.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct revelation: "And they will kill him, and he will be raised on the third day." And they were greatly distressed." The passion prediction ends with the resurrection as its inseparable counterpart — kill and raise, death and third-day vindication. The disciples\' distress (<em>elypēthēsan sphodra</em>) shows they hear the death but do not yet comprehend the resurrection. The Christological pattern: the passion predictions consistently pair suffering with resurrection, but the disciples consistently hear only the suffering. Understanding the resurrection is the hermeneutical key to all that follows.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "When they came to Capernaum, the collectors of the two-drachma tax came to Peter and said, \'Does your teacher not pay the tax?\'" The temple tax question — the half-shekel assessment required of every Jewish male (Exod 30:13-16) — creates the occasion for Jesus\' statement about sonship and freedom (v.26). The collectors\' question about "your teacher" is the respectful but slightly distancing address of those who are not disciples. The answer Jesus gives will reveal his unique relationship to the Temple and its Lord.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation: "He said, \'Yes.\' And when he came into the house, Jesus spoke to him first, saying, \'What do you think, Simon? From whom do kings of the earth take toll or tax? From their sons or from others?\'" Jesus\' question to Peter — before Peter has reported the tax-collector conversation — again shows his knowledge of what has occurred (cf. 12:25: "knowing their thoughts"). The question about kings\' sons is the setup for the Christological claim: the son of the king does not pay the king\'s tax. Jesus is the Son of the King whose house the temple is.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation: "And when he said, \'From others,\' Jesus said to him, \'Then the sons are free.\'" The Christological claim is elegant: if kings\' sons are exempt from their father\'s taxes, then the Son of God is exempt from the temple tax — because the temple is his Father\'s house (21:13: "my house"). The freedom of the Son is the freedom of the one who inhabits the Father\'s house by right, not by duty. The statement "the sons are free" carries the eschatological weight of the freedom Christ will purchase for those who are adopted as sons through him (Rom 8:15-17).</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "However, not to give offense to them, go to the sea and cast a hook and take the first fish that comes up, and when you open its mouth you will find a shekel. Take that and give it to them for me and for yourself." The miraculous provision of the tax-coin from the fish\'s mouth is the Christological combination of the freedom of the Son with the grace of the servant: he is free from the obligation but pays it voluntarily to avoid giving offense. The fish that provides the coin anticipates the feeding miracles\' pattern — provision through ordinary means (fishing) by extraordinary divine knowledge and control. He pays his own tax from the abundance of creation.</p>'
  }
}

